        title: 'The market that resulted',
        html: `<p>Mobile gaming revenue surpassed combined PC and console gaming revenue globally around 2018 and has continued to grow since. The majority of that revenue comes from a small percentage of players — the "whales" who make large discretionary purchases within free-to-play games — while the majority of players engage for free and generate no direct revenue. The market structure is unusual compared to other entertainment categories: a mobile game with a hundred million downloads might generate most of its revenue from a few hundred thousand paying players, with the non-paying majority serving primarily as the social network that makes the paying minority's engagement meaningful in games with social components.</p>
<p>The design implications of the free-to-play model are visible across the mobile game landscape and, increasingly, in the console and PC games that have adopted similar monetization approaches. Games designed around free-to-play economics are games designed around engagement metrics: how often players return, how long each session lasts, and at what moments in the session players are most likely to make purchases. These metrics shape design decisions at every level, from the timing of difficulty spikes (calibrated to produce purchase opportunities) to the visual design of reward systems (optimised for the dopaminergic engagement patterns that drive session length). The design language of free-to-play mobile games is a design language of engagement optimisation, and its influence on games made for audiences who never thought of themselves as mobile players is the least-discussed consequence of mobile gaming's rise to commercial dominance.</p>`,
